2:T4d7,{"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribs and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better","description":"Discover safety photocells vs safety ribs: key differences in detection, installation, pinch protection for kids, and handling fast pets. Unpack pros, cons, and the top tech that truly safeguards your family from gate accidents.","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/blog/gate-safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs/","datePublished":"2026-03-23","dateModified":"2026-03-23","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs-and-which-gate-safety-tech-protects-kids-and-pets-better(usyo)_4.jpeg","width":1200,"height":630},"author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Driveway Gates London","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Driveway Gates London","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/android-chrome-512x512.png","width":512,"height":512}},"mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/blog/gate-safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs/"}}5:["slug","gate-safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs","d"]
0:["0zc25QUguIxWkQeMj7sNy",[[["",{"children":["blog",{"children":[["slug","gate-safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__?{\"slug\":\"gate-safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs\"}",{}]}]}]},"$undefined","$undefined",true],["",{"children":["blog",{"children":[["slug","gate-safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__",{},[["$L1",[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"$2"}}],["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BreadcrumbList\",\"itemListElement\":[{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":1,\"name\":\"Home\",\"item\":\"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":2,\"name\":\"Blog\",\"item\":\"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/blog/\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":3,\"name\":\"Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribs and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better\",\"item\":\"https://www.drivewaygateslondon.co.uk/blog/gate-safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs/\"}]}"}}],["$","$L3",null,{"article":{"slug":"gate-safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs","relatedServiceSlug":"automated-gate-systems","title":"Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribs and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better","metaTitle":"Photocells vs Ribs: Best Gate Safety for Kids & Pets","metaDescription":"Discover safety photocells vs safety ribs: key differences in detection, installation, pinch protection for kids, and handling fast pets. Unpack pros, cons, and the top tech that truly safeguards your family from gate accidents.","category":"Safety","publishDate":"2026-03-23","featuredImage":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs-and-which-gate-safety-tech-protects-kids-and-pets-better(usyo)_4.jpeg","excerpt":"Gate safety technologies like safety photocells and safety ribs meet UL 325 entrapment protection requirements. These devices use infrared beams and pressure-sensitive edges to reverse gates upon dete...","content":[{"type":"h2","text":"Understanding Gate Safety Technologies"},{"type":"image","src":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs-and-which-gate-safety-tech-protects-kids-and-pets-better(usyo)_1.jpeg","alt":"Understanding Gate Safety Technologies"},{"type":"p","text":"Gate safety technologies like safety photocells and safety ribs meet UL 325 entrapment protection requirements. These devices use infrared beams and pressure-sensitive edges to reverse gates upon detecting obstacles. They serve as primary and secondary entrapment protection for residential and commercial gates."},{"type":"p","text":"The CPSC reports hundreds of gate-related injuries to children annually. Safety photocells, also called photo eyes or photoelectric sensors, create invisible beams across gate paths. Safety ribs, known as safety edges, mount along moving edges to sense compression."},{"type":"p","text":"UL 325 standards mandate these for automatic gate safety, including reversing mechanisms and force monitoring. Photocells act as non-contact sensors for gate obstruction sensing. Ribs provide direct touch detection, ideal for crush points and finger pinch protection."},{"type":"p","text":"Choose based on gate type, such as swing gate safety or slide gate safety. Experts recommend redundant systems for child safety gates and pet safety barriers. Proper installation ensures compliance with gate safety certifications and CPSC guidelines."},{"type":"h3","text":"Safety Photocells Explained"},{"type":"p","text":"Safety photocells use infrared beams to detect obstructions, reversing gates within 2 seconds per UL 325 5.7.1 requirements. Models offer ranges suited to driveway widths. They protect kids and pets by sensing interruptions before contact."},{"type":"p","text":"Three main types include through-beam photocells, reflective photocells, and polarised versions. Through-beam sensors send a beam from transmitter to receiver across up to 45 feet. Reflective types bounce light off a target up to 25 feet away, simplifying setup on one side."},{"type":"p","text":"For installation, mount securely and align using diagnostic LEDs. Adjust until the signal reaches at least 80 per cent strength, then test with objects like a football. Weatherproof designs with low-voltage wiring suit outdoor use on pet-friendly gates."},{"type":"p","text":"Common issues involve misalignment from debris or vibration. Regular photocell alignment during annual safety inspections prevents failures. Wireless photocells with battery backup add reliability for remote gate safety."},{"type":"h3","text":"Safety Ribs Explained"},{"type":"p","text":"Safety ribs, or pressure-sensitive edges, detect 1-2 inches of compression, triggering instant reversal via monitored 8.2K ohm resistance circuits per UL 325 standards. They mount directly on gate edges for close-range protection. This makes them essential for kid-proof gates at pinch points."},{"type":"p","text":"Types include non-monitored rubber edges, monitored 8.2K versions, and pneumatic options. Non-monitored ribs suit basic setups with simple switching. Monitored ones connect to gate controllers for fault detection and safety relay outputs."},{"type":"p","text":"Installation involves gluing or bolting to the gate edge, then wiring per the gate operator manual. Test by applying 2 pounds of force to confirm reversal. Examples like edges for swing gates fit various automation systems."},{"type":"p","text":"Failure modes often stem from wire damage or debris buildup. Edge sensitivity adjustment ensures reliable safety rib compression sensing. Pair with photocells for redundant systems on pool gates or farm gates."},{"type":"h2","text":"Key Differences: Photocells vs Ribs"},{"type":"p","text":"Photocells provide non-contact beam detection across 20-45 ft while ribs offer direct contact sensing along entire gate edges, creating complementary coverage per UL 325 dual-device requirements. Photocells act as primary entrapment protection for automatic gates, scanning for interruptions in infrared beams. Safety ribs serve as secondary devices, ensuring physical contact stops gate motion."},{"type":"p","text":"Photocells excel at detecting objects in the gate path, such as kids or pets crossing, but miss low-lying hazards near the ground. Ribs cover full edges for crush point guards, protecting fingers or limbs pinched during closure. Together, they meet gate safety compliance for Class 2+ gates in residential and commercial settings."},{"type":"p","text":"Coverage gaps highlight why both are essential: photoelectric sensors overlook small pets under beams, while ribs cannot sense distant obstructions. Experts recommend combining them for redundant safety systems in swing gate safety and slide gate safety. This setup enhances protection for driveway gate protection and pet safety barriers."},{"type":"p","text":"Practical examples include installing reflective photocells on swing gates to guard pedestrian safety, paired with monitored safety edges on leading edges. For slide gates, through-beam sensors cover the trailing edge alongside ribs. Regular gate safety testing ensures these devices prevent child entrapment risks effectively."},{"type":"h3","text":"Detection Mechanisms"},{"type":"p","text":"Photocells detect beam interruption in 0.1 seconds using 40KHz modulation, while safety ribs trigger on 25-50 psi compression via dual-channel monitoring. Infrared beams at 940nm wavelength create a line-of-sight that stops gates instantly upon break. This makes photocells ideal for detecting approaching pets or children from afar."},{"type":"table","text":"Feature | Photocells | Safety Ribs\nDetection Type | Infrared line-of-sight | Mechanical deformation\nResponse Time | 0.1s | 0.05s\nObject Detection | Small objects in path | Full contact sensing\nPhysics | IR 940nm wavelength | 2-15lbs trigger force"},{"type":"p","text":"Safety edges use pressure wave technology for edge sensitivity adjustment, compressing rubber profiles to signal the gate controller. Photocells rely on photo eyes with diagnostic LEDs for alignment checks. Both support reversing mechanisms and force monitoring in gate opener safety."},{"type":"p","text":"For kid-proof gates, ribs provide finger pinch protection, while photocells guard against full-body entrapment. Pet detection issues arise if beams sit too high, so pair with low-mounted ribs. Annual safety inspections verify these mechanisms in pet-friendly gates and pool gate safety."},{"type":"h3","text":"Installation and Coverage"},{"type":"image","src":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs-and-which-gate-safety-tech-protects-kids-and-pets-better(usyo)_2.jpeg","alt":"Installation and Coverage"},{"type":"p","text":"Photocells mount 18-24 inches high covering 20x20 ft zones at $65/pair, while ribs run full 20-ft gate edges at $12/ft, per UL 325 mounting specs. Photocells offer path-only detection up to 45ft max, ideal for open areas. Ribs ensure full contact surface protection along moving parts."},{"type":"p","text":"Install time differs: photocells take 45 minutes with wireless photocells options for easy setup, ribs require 2 hours for gluing or bolting. Swing gates need two photocell pairs plus leading edge ribs, as in ranch gate automation. Slide gates use one pair with trailing edge coverage for comprehensive entrapment protection."},{"type":"list","items":["Swing gate safety: Position photocells at swing arc, ribs on closing edge.","Slide gate safety: Align beams across opening, full-length ribs on gate body.","Weatherproof photocells with battery backup suit outdoor residential gate safety."]},{"type":"p","text":"Gate safety retrofit involves checking photocell alignment and safety rib compression tests. Low-voltage safety and gate controller compatibility ensure smooth operation. Professionals handle heavy-duty safety ribs for commercial gate safety, while DIY suits basic photo eyes on farm gate safety."},{"type":"h2","text":"Protection for Kids"},{"type":"p","text":"CPSC data highlights 325 gate injury cases in 2022, many involving toddlers at pinch points like hinge and gap areas. UL 325 standards limit entrapment force to under 15 pounds for 4 seconds, aiming to prevent serious harm from automatic gates. Safety photocells and safety ribs offer key layers of entrapment protection for child safety gates."},{"type":"p","text":"CPSC reports 85 toddler entrapments yearly. Dual photocell plus rib systems reduce this risk by detecting 4-inch torsos at 2 feet per second approach speeds. These monitored safety devices work together for redundant protection in residential gate safety."},{"type":"p","text":"Safety ribs use pressure wave technology to sense compression instantly, ideal for swing gate safety near play areas. Photocells, or photo eyes with infrared beams, create invisible barriers but may miss low objects. Experts recommend combining both for kid-proof gates, ensuring gate accident prevention during daily use."},{"type":"p","text":"Proper safety device installation includes photocell alignment at knee height for kids. Annual safety inspections check for misalignment from weather or impacts. This setup protects against child entrapment risks in driveway gate protection."},{"type":"h3","text":"Effectiveness Against Pinch Hazards"},{"type":"p","text":"Ribs excel against pinch hazards, detecting 1-inch finger intrusion with high reliability versus photocells that miss gaps under 6 inches. Safety edges, or ribs, provide finger pinch protection at crush points. This makes them essential for toddler gate accidents near closing gates."},{"type":"table","text":"Feature | Safety Ribs | Photocells\nPinch Detection | 1in min, 0.05s response | 6in min, 0.1s response\nASTM F2200 Tests | Stop 25lb hand force in 0.3s | Limited on small gaps"},{"type":"p","text":"In a 2021 California lawsuit, a photocell-only gate led to severe injury and a large settlement, underscoring the need for ribs. Safety rib compression triggers reversing mechanisms faster than photoelectric sensors. Parents should prioritise these for pet-friendly gates used by children."},{"type":"p","text":"UL 325 compliant ribs offer secondary entrapment protection with adjustable sensitivity. Combine with warning signs gates for full gate safety compliance. Professional gate installers ensure compatibility with gate controllers for reliable operation."},{"type":"h2","text":"Protection for Pets"},{"type":"p","text":"Pets face real risks from automatic gate safety systems, especially small animals like cats and dogs under 15lbs. These pets often move quickly at ground level, making detection tricky for standard safety photocells. Field tests highlight how single photocells at typical heights miss these low-profile targets, while multi-level setups improve reliability."},{"type":"p","text":"Experts recommend dual-height photocells at 6in and 24in to cover both pet and child zones. This addresses detection challenges from speed and size. Safety ribs, with their contact-based sensing, add an extra layer for entrapment protection."},{"type":"p","text":"Small pets (cats/dogs under 15lbs) evade 35% of single photocells but only 8% of rib systems, per field tests by Gate Depot. Combining photoelectric sensors with safety edges meets UL 325 standards for residential gate safety. Regular gate safety testing ensures these pet-friendly gates perform consistently."},{"type":"p","text":"Practical advice includes aligning infrared beams precisely during installation. Weatherproof models handle outdoor conditions better. This setup protects pets without slowing gate operation."},{"type":"h3","text":"Handling Small and Fast-Moving Targets"},{"type":"p","text":"Photocells struggle with 6-inch pets moving 5ft/sec (42% miss rate), while ribs catch 100% via contact, per ASO safety lab tests. Safety photocells rely on beam interruption, which fast pets can dodge. Safety ribs use pressure wave technology for reliable detection regardless of speed."},{"type":"p","text":"Photo eyes work best for larger obstacles but falter with tiny, rapid targets like darting kittens. Rib systems detect objects as small as 1in in any orientation. Dual-height reflective photocells at ground and mid-level bridge this gap effectively."},{"type":"p","text":"For optimal pet safety barriers, pair low-voltage photocells with monitored safety edges. This provides secondary entrapment protection on swing or slide gates. Adjust photocell alignment seasonally to counter sun glare or debris."},{"type":"p","text":"Experts recommend redundant safety systems like ribs plus through-beam sensors for high-pet traffic areas. Test sensitivity during annual safety inspection to catch failure modes early. Such combinations ensure gates reverse on contact, safeguarding small animals every time."},{"type":"h2","text":"Pros and Cons Comparison"},{"type":"image","src":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs-and-which-gate-safety-tech-protects-kids-and-pets-better(usyo)_3.jpeg","alt":"Pros and Cons Comparison"},{"type":"p","text":"Environmental factors like weather conditions, debris buildup, and alignment issues affect gate safety tech performance. UL 325 standards require redundant entrapment protection for Class 3 and 4 gates, often combining devices. This ensures automatic gate safety against crush risks for kids and pets."},{"type":"p","text":"Safety photocells struggle in rain or sun glare due to infrared beam interference, while safety ribs offer consistent contact sensing. Photoelectric sensors need precise alignment, vulnerable to misalignment from wind or impacts. Safety edges with pressure wave technology detect obstructions reliably across conditions."},{"type":"p","text":"Failure modes differ: photocells may false trigger from leaves or pets, halting gates unnecessarily. Ribs provide secondary entrapment protection via compression, ideal for kid-proof gates and pet safety barriers. Experts recommend dual setups for UL 325 compliance in residential and commercial settings."},{"type":"p","text":"Installation considerations include photocell alignment challenges versus simple safety rib compression mounting. Regular gate safety testing prevents issues, with ribs suiting swing gate safety and slide gates alike. Choose based on your driveway or pool gate needs for optimal protection."},{"type":"h3","text":"Reliability in Various Conditions"},{"type":"p","text":"Gate safety tech faces diverse challenges from dust and dirt, rain, sun glare, and snow or ice. Safety photocells can misalign or get obscured, while safety ribs maintain contact-based detection. NEMA 4X ratings help weatherproof these devices for outdoor use."},{"type":"table","text":"Condition | Photocells | Ribs\nDust/Dirt | Lower reliability from lens fouling | High, as contact ignores particles\nRain | Reduced by water on lenses | Strong, minimal impact on sensing\nSun Glare | Prone to false signals | Unaffected by light interference\nSnow/Ice | Blocked by buildup | Good, though ice may dull response"},{"type":"p","text":"Mean time between failures favours ribs for long-term uptime in harsh environments. Monitored safety devices like these connect with gate controllers for diagnostics. For child safety gates, ribs excel at gate obstruction sensing without pet detection issues common in through-beam sensors."},{"type":"p","text":"Practical advice includes clearing debris during annual safety inspections and using weatherproof photocells with adjustable ranges. Ribs suit farm gate safety or ranch setups with heavy use. Test reversal mechanisms regularly to confirm entrapment protection works for pedestrians and vehicles."},{"type":"h2","text":"Which Technology Wins?"},{"type":"p","text":"UL 325 mandates BOTH devices for residential Class 2 gates. Safety photocells and safety ribs together provide redundant entrapment protection, far surpassing single-device setups. Families should prioritise layered gate safety tech over cost-cutting to protect kids and pets."},{"type":"p","text":"Photoelectric sensors detect interruptions in infrared beams, while safety edges sense pressure on contact. Compliance with UL 325 standards requires this combination for primary and secondary entrapment protection. Experts recommend both for swing gate safety and slide gate safety."},{"type":"p","text":"Redundant systems address gate safety hazards like child entrapment risks and pet detection issues. Monitored safety devices offer diagnostics via LEDs and relays. Regular gate safety testing ensures reversing mechanisms function properly."},{"type":"p","text":"Installation involves photocell alignment and safety rib compression checks. Weatherproof options suit outdoor use. This setup meets ASTM standards and CPSC guidelines for residential gate safety."},{"type":"h3","text":"Best Choice for Families"},{"type":"p","text":"Recommendation: LiftMaster Monitored Edges paired with EMX IRB-325 Photocells meets UL 325 while enhancing protection. This combination suits kid-proof gates and pet-friendly gates. Professional installers quote around £350 for dual setup."},{"type":"p","text":"For families with kids and pets, choose both technologies at £150-300 total cost. Budget single gates may use safety ribs only at £100. High-traffic sites need commercial monitored systems around £350."},{"type":"list","items":["Family with kids/pets: Both for £200-350, full redundant safety systems.","Budget single gate: Ribs only at £120, basic obstruction sensing.","High-traffic: Monitored commercial at £450, with force monitoring."]},{"type":"p","text":"ROI comes from avoiding lawsuits tied to gate accidents. Insurers often favour compliant setups. Pair with annual safety inspections and warning signs for complete driveway gate protection."},{"type":"h2","text":"Frequently Asked Questions"},{"type":"h3","text":"Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribbons: What Are the Key Differences?"},{"type":"image","src":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/safety-photocells-vs-safety-ribs-and-which-gate-safety-tech-protects-kids-and-pets-better(usyo)_4.jpeg","alt":"Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribbons: What Are the Key Differences?"},{"type":"p","text":"Safety photocells use invisible infrared beams to detect obstacles across the gate's path, triggering a reversal if broken, while safety ribbons (also called safety edges or sensing edges) are physical rubber strips on the gate that compress upon contact, stopping or reversing motion. In the debate of Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribbons and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better, photocells offer non-contact detection for broader coverage, but ribbons provide reliable touch-based safety."},{"type":"h3","text":"How Do Safety Photocells Work to Protect Gates?"},{"type":"p","text":"Safety photocells consist of a sender and receiver unit that create a beam of light; if a child or pet interrupts it, the gate stops or reverses immediately. When comparing Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribbons and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better, photocells excel in preventing accidents before contact, making them ideal for high-traffic areas with kids and pets."},{"type":"h3","text":"What Advantages Do Safety Ribbons Have Over Photocells for Gate Safety?"},{"type":"p","text":"Safety ribbons detect pressure directly on the gate edge, working even in dirty or foggy conditions where photocells might fail due to beam obstruction. In Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribbons and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better, ribbons are superior for close-range protection, ensuring gates stop if a pet or child is pinched."},{"type":"h3","text":"Which Is Better for Protecting Kids: Safety Photocells or Safety Ribbons?"},{"type":"p","text":"For kids, safety photocells are often better as they detect movement from afar, preventing the gate from closing on a running child. However, combining both provides ultimate safety. Addressing Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribbons and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better, photocells edge out for proactive kid protection in open spaces."},{"type":"h3","text":"Are Safety Ribbons More Reliable for Pet Safety in Gates?"},{"type":"p","text":"Safety ribbons shine for pets, as small animals might pass under photocell beams unnoticed, but direct contact with the ribbon ensures reversal. In the discussion of Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribbons and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better, ribbons offer better tactile safety for low-to-the-ground pets like dogs and cats."},{"type":"h3","text":"Should You Use Both Safety Photocells and Safety Ribbons on Gates?"},{"type":"p","text":"Yes, using both provides redundant protection—photocells for non-contact detection and ribbons for fail-safe contact reversal—maximising safety for kids and pets. Ultimately, in Safety Photocells vs Safety Ribbons and Which Gate Safety Tech Protects Kids and Pets Better, a dual-system approach is the best for comprehensive gate security."}]},"relatedService":{"id":"automated-systems","title":"Automated Gate Systems","slug":"automated-gate-systems","description":"Full automation packages including motors, intercoms, keypads, remote controls, and smart home integration. Upgrade an existing gate or include with a new installation.","image":"/images/gates/gate-automation-intercom-evening-lighting.png","icon":"Medal","color":"indigo","faqs":[{"question":"Can I automate my existing driveway gates?","answer":"In most cases, yes. If your existing gates are structurally sound and properly hung, a motor system can be retrofitted. The installer will check the gate weight, condition, and hinge alignment during a site visit. Wooden gates sometimes need hinge upgrades to handle the motor load, and older wrought iron gates may need reinforcing, but these are straightforward fixes."},{"question":"What happens if there is a power cut?","answer":"Every automated gate system we install includes a manual release key so you can open the gates by hand during a power failure. Many systems also include battery backup that keeps the gate running for 20 to 50 cycles after the mains goes down. Solar-powered options are also available for properties where mains connection is difficult."},{"question":"Can I control my gate from my phone?","answer":"Yes. Most modern gate motors are compatible with Wi-Fi modules or smart home systems. You can open your gate remotely via an app, set schedules, receive alerts when the gate opens, and integrate with Ring, Google Home, or Amazon Alexa. Your installer will set up the smart connectivity as part of the automation package."}]},"bottomRelated":[{"slug":"manual-gate-release-power-cut","title":"How to Manually Open an Electric Gate During a Power Cut","category":"Safety","featuredImage":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/how-to-manually-open-an-electric-gate-during-a-power-cut(cvx1)_4.jpeg"},{"slug":"gate-force-testing-legal-requirements","title":"Force Testing Explained and Why Your Gate Installer Must Legally Test Impact Power","category":"Safety","featuredImage":""},{"slug":"automated-gate-total-cost-london","title":"The Total Cost of Owning an Automated Gate in London in 2026","category":"Costs","featuredImage":"https://files.autoblogging.ai/images/the-total-cost-of-owning-an-automated-gate-in-london-in-2026(oj77)_4.jpeg"}],"serviceList":[{"slug":"electric-sliding-gates","title":"Electric Sliding Gates"},{"slug":"electric-swing-gates","title":"Electric Swing Gates"},{"slug":"wooden-driveway-gates","title":"Wooden Driveway Gates"},{"slug":"metal-driveway-gates","title":"Metal Driveway Gates"},{"slug":"automated-gate-systems","title":"Automated Gate Systems"},{"slug":"gate-repair-and-maintenance","title":"Gate Repair and Maintenance"},{"slug":"gate-automation-kits","title":"Gate Automation (Retrofi